  "response_text": "**Time Complexity of Merge Sort**\n================================\n\nMerge sort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that splits a list of elements into two halves, recursively sorts each half, and then merges the two sorted halves. The time complexity of merge sort is O(n log n).\n\n**Why O(n log n)?**\n\nTo understand why merge sort has a time complexity of O(n log n), let's break down the steps involved in the algorithm:\n\n1.  **Divide**: The list is divided into two halves until each half has only one element (i.e., the base case).\n2.  **Conquer**: Each half is recursively sorted.\n3.  **Combine**: The two sorted halves are merged to form a single sorted list.\n\nThe key insight is that the number of elements in each half is roughly halved at each level of recursion. This is because we're dividing the list in half at each step.\n\n**Mathematical Analysis**\n\nLet's analyze the time complexity using a mathematical approach",
